<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-486-592  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 486 592.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  May 21 1990 v12 n21 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users look to coprocessors for speed: math coprocessors arefinding acceptance among general users. (Market Update)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dryden, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Math coprocessors do not benefit all microcomputer applications,but the chips are included in about one third of all Intel80386-based microcomputers sold today.andP;  Spreadsheet users feel thechips help their software's performance and almost allcomputer-aided design users and engineers running math-intensivesimulations report increased performance.andP;  Word processing, dataentry, data base management, publishing and font manipulationprograms do not show a marked performance increase.andP;  Certainfeatures of graphics programs show increased performance, but amath coprocessor does not effect the entire program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Mathematics of ComputingCoprocessorsMarket ShareMarket SurveyTrendsIntegrated CircuitsUser Behavior.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>